FAO WRLFMD Genotyping Report of 6 Feb 2014, FMDV type O, Israel, BATCH: WRLFMD/2014/00001, 6 samples
----------------------------------------------------------------------
The report addresses the following 6 genotyped samples from Israel (all received at WRL on 24 Jan 2014):
WRLFMD Ref No // locality, region // collection date // species // tissue // topotype // strain
----------------------------------------------------------------------
ISR/1/2014 // Iksal, Hazafon (=north) // 11 Jan 2014 // sheep // heart // ME-SA // PanAsia-2FAR-09
ISR/2/2014 // Iksal, Hazafon (=north) // 11 Jan 2014 // sheep // heart // ME-SA // PanAsia-2FAR-09
ISR/3/2014 // Iksal, Hazafon (=north) // 12 Jan 2014 // sheep // heart // ME-SA // PanAsia-2FAR-09
ISR/4/2014:// Iksal, Hazafon (=north) // 12 Jan 2014 // sheep // heart // ME-SA // PanAsia-2FAR-09

ISR/5/2014:// Tirah, Hamerkaz (=centre) // 15 Jan 2014 // sheep // heart // ME-SA // PanAsia-2FAR-09
ISR/6/2014:// Tirah, Hamerkaz (=centre) // 16 Jan 2014 // sheep // heart // ME-SA // PanAsia-2FAR-09

The sequencing of the 4 samples from Iksal showed the following viruses to be most closely related:

virus name // percent identity // percent difference // topotype // strain
----------------------------------------------------------------------
O/PAT/13/2013 * // 99.69 // 0.31 // ME-SA // PanAsia-2FAR-09
O/PAT/14/2013 * // 99.69 // 0.31 // ME-SA // PanAsia-2FAR-09
O/ISR/5/2014 ** // 98.90 // 1.10 // ME-SA // PanAsia-2FAR-09
O/ISR/6/2014 ** // 98.90 // 1.10 // ME-SA // PanAsia-2FAR-09
O/SAU/1/2009 // 98.44 // 1.56 // ME-SA // PanAsia-2FAR-09
O/SAU/2/2009 // 98.44 // 1.56 // ME-SA // PanAsia-2FAR-09
O/TUR/12/2013 // 98.44 // 1.56 // ME-SA // PanAsia-2FAR-09
* Collected 21-24 Nov 2013 from sheep in Jericho, West Bank, Palestinian authority (see ProMED-mail post 20131209.2101647).
** Collected 15-16 Jan 2014 from sheep in Tirah, central Israel (see above and post 20140208.2264193).

The sequencing of the 4 samples from Iksal showed the following reference virus to be most closely related:
O/IRN/31/2009 (identity 98.12 percent).

The sequencing of the 2 samples from Tirah showed the following reference virus to be most closely related:
O/IRN/31/2009 (identity 97.50 percent).

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The recent epizootic of FMDV serotype O reportedly started in November 2013. It initially affected young unvaccinated beef cattle on the Golan heights (bordering Syria and Lebanon), followed by an outbreak during the same month in sheep in Jericho (West Bank, Palestinian authority). Later, in January 2014, additional outbreaks were reported, namely from 2 sheep flocks in north (Iksal) and central (Tirah) Israel and (unofficially) in several sheep/goat flocks in the West Bank (Palestinian Authority). Routinely, timely preventively vaccinated animals seem not to have been affected. According to the genotyping performed by the WRLFMD, all 12 samples submitted since November 2013 (9 from cattle and sheep in Israel and 3 from sheep in the West Bank) were found to be of topotype ME-SA, strain PanAsia-2FAR-09, closely related to recent Turkish isolates.

The previous, 2012 FMD event in Israel was caused by a different (serotype O) virus strain, namely 'ME-SA PanAsia-2 ANT-10'.

Israel's FMD situation has been characterised for decades by seasonality and by periodic new introductions of the virus, particularly from the north-eastern borders. The route(s) and source(s) of the FMDV introductions and possible role played by wild boar, are subject to ongoing investigations (see ref below). A presentation "FMD in Israel" by Israel's CVO, including data collected during 1974 - (June) 2013, is available at http://www.fao.org/fileadmin/user_upload/eufmd/40thGeneral_session_documents/40General_Session/App22_IsraelNGalon.pdf.

Subscribers may wish to visit the relevant web-pages of the WRLFMD at http://www.wrlfmd.org/fmd_genotyping/me/isr.htm and http://www.wrlfmd.org/fmd_genotyping/me/pat.htm.

Reference
---------
Stram Y, Engel O, Rubinstein M, et al: Multiple invasions of O1 FMDV serotype into Israel revealed by genetic analysis of VP1 genes of Israeli isolates from 1989 to 2007. Vet Microbiol 2011; 147(3-4); 398-402. Abstract available at http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20702050. - Mod.AS

